## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `ProductCatalogTests.cs`

### Summary

**10 tests analyzed · 8 Critical · 1 High · 1 Medium · 0 Low**

This is a textbook **coverage-touching** test suite. Every public method on `ProductCatalog` is called (achieving high line coverage), but almost nothing is actually verified. These tests will pass even if every method returns garbage or silently corrupts data.

---

### 🔴 Critical — Tests giving false confidence

#### 1. Coverage Touching (systemic — 10/10 tests)

The entire class follows a pattern: call a method, maybe `Assert.IsNotNull`, move on. Tests are in near-declaration order of the production class. This inflates coverage to 95% while verifying almost nothing.

#### 2. No Assertions (4 tests)

These tests have **zero assertions** — they pass no matter what the code does:

| Test | Line | What's unverified |
|------|------|-------------------|
| `AddProduct_Works` | 17–21 | Product was actually persisted |
| `UpdatePrice_Works` | 32–36 | Price was actually changed |
| `RemoveProduct_Works` | 39–43 | Product was actually deleted |
| `GetProductCount_Works` | 63–66 | Count value is never checked |
| `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` | 68–74 | Prices were actually discounted |
| `ImportFromCsv_Works` | 84–88 | Products were actually imported |

**Fix example** — `AddProduct_Works` (line 17):
```csharp
// BEFORE — passes even if AddProduct is a no-op
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_Works()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);
}

// AFTER — verifies the product was persisted correctly
[TestMethod]
public void AddProduct_StoresProductRetrievableBySku()
{
    var product = new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m);
    _catalog.AddProduct(product);

    var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
    Assert.AreEqual("SKU-001", retrieved?.Sku);
    Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved?.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved?.Price);
}
```

**Fix example** — `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32):
```csharp
// BEFORE — passes even if UpdatePrice silently does nothing
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_Works()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
    _catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
}

// AFTER — verifies the price was actually changed
[TestMethod]
public void UpdatePrice_ChangesPersistedPrice()
{
    _catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
